    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nExecuting `nvim_buf_delete()` to delete a non-current buffer while inside a floating window changes focused window.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create an 'init.lua' with the following content:\n\n    ```lua\n    local buf_id_normal = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(true, false)\n    vim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(buf_id_normal)\n\n    vim.schedule(function()\n      local buf_id_float = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\n      local config = { relative = 'editor', row = 2, col = 2, height = 2, width = 10 }\n      vim.api.nvim_open_win(buf_id_float, true, config)\n    end)\n\n    _G.buf_del = function() vim.api.nvim_buf_delete(buf_id_normal, { force = true }) end\n    ```\n\n2. `nvim --clean -u init.lua`. Floating window is current.\n3. `:lua _G.buf_del()`. This deletes the buffer in the normal window, but keeps the focus on it.\n\nThis started to happen after #39800. Before it, the normal buffer is not deleted, but the focus is also not changed.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nDeleting a non-current buffer should never change the current window. Ideally, not even temporarily with window-related events as side effects. But at least not permanently which affects actual usage.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-520+g8e1d6dfada\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 7.0.8-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nBoth Appimage and from source",
