            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Another somewhat problematic side effect that this introduces is that `nvim_buf_delete()` now triggers `BufEnter` for that buffer. Can be verified with this 'init.lua':\n\n```lua\nlocal buf_id_normal = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(true, false)\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(buf_id_normal)\n\n_G.log = {}\n\nvim.schedule(function()\n  local buf_id_float = vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true)\n  local config = { relative = 'editor', row = 2, col = 2, height = 2, width = 10 }\n  vim.api.nvim_open_win(buf_id_float, true, config)\n\n  local cb = function(ev) table.insert(_G.log, ev.buf) end\n  vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('BufEnter', { buffer = buf_id_normal, callback = cb })\nend)\n\n_G.buf_del = function() vim.api.nvim_buf_delete(buf_id_normal, { force = true }) end\n```\n\nAfter executing `:lua buf_del()`, the `:=log` shows `{ 2 }`. And before it was empty.\n\nThis can be problematic. At least because (as far as I can tell) `BufEnter` is not triggered when deleting a buffer with a normal window as current.",
